#Text=V. A Girl Captain
#Text=When Wilbur came on deck the morning after the sinking of the bark he was surprised to find the schooner under way again .
#Text=Wilbur and Charlie had berthed forward during that night -- Charlie with the hands , Wilbur in the Captain 's hammock .
#Text=The reason for this change of quarters had been found in a peremptory order from Moran during the dog-watch the preceding evening .
#Text=She had looked squarely at Wilbur from under her scowl , and had said briefly and in a fine contralto voice , that he had for the first time noted :
#Text=“ I berth aft , in the cabin ; you and the Chinaman forward .
#Text=Understand ? ”

#Text=Moran had only forestalled Wilbur 's intention ; while after her almost miraculous piece of seamanship in the rescue of the schooner , Charlie and the Chinese crew accorded her a respect that was almost superstitious .
#Text=Wilbur met her again at breakfast .

#Text=She was still wearing men 's clothing -- part of Kitchell 's outfit -- and was booted to the knee ; but now she wore no hat , and her enormous mane of rye-colored hair was braided into long strands near to the thickness of a man 's arm .
#Text=The redness of her face gave a startling effect to her pale blue eyes and sandy , heavy eyebrows , that easily lowered to a frown .
#Text=She ate with her knife , and after pushing away her plate Wilbur observed that she drank half a tumbler of whiskey and water .
#Text=The conversation between the two was tame enough .
#Text=There was no common ground upon which they could meet .
#Text=To her father 's death -- no doubt an old matter even before her rescue -- she made no allusion .
#Text=Her attitude toward Wilbur was one of defiance and suspicion .
#Text=Only once did she relax :
#Text=“ How did you come to be aboard here with these rat-eaters -- you 're no sailor ? ” she said abruptly .
#Text=“ Huh ! ” laughed Wilbur , mirthlessly ;
#Text=“ huh !
#Text=I was shanghaied . ”
#Text=Moran smote the table with a red fist , and shouted with sonorous , bell-toned laughter .
#Text=“ Shanghaied ? --
#Text=you ?
#Text=Now , that is really good .
#Text=And what are you going to do now ? ”
#Text=“ What are you going to do ? ”
#Text=“ Signal the first home-bound vessel and be taken into Frisco .
#Text=I 've my insurance to collect ( Wilbur had given her the ' Letty 's ' papers ) and the disaster to report . ”
#Text=“ Well , I 'm not keen on shark-hunting myself , ” said Wilbur .
#Text=But Moran showed no interest in his plans .
#Text=However , they soon found that they were not to be permitted to signal .
#Text=At noon the same day the schooner sighted a steamship 's smoke on the horizon , and began to raise her rapidly .
#Text=Moran immediately bound on the ensign , union down , and broke it out at the peak .
#Text=Charlie , who was at the wheel , spoke a sentence in Chinese , and one of the hands drew his knife across the halyards and brought the distress signal to the deck .
#Text=Moran turned upon Charlie with an oath , her brows knitted .
#Text=“ No !
#Text=No ! ” sang Charlie , closing his eyes and wagging his head .
#Text=“ No !
#Text=Too muchee los ' time ; no can stop .
#Text=You come downside cabin ; you an ' one-piece boss number two ( this was Wilbur )
#Text=have um chin-chin . ”
#Text=The odd conclave assembled about Kitchell 's table -- the club-man , the half-masculine girl in men 's clothes , and the Chinaman .
#Text=The conference was an angry one , Wilbur and Moran insisting that they be put aboard the steamship , Charlie refusing with calm obstinacy .
#Text=“ I have um chin-chin with China boys las ' nigh ' .
#Text=China boy heap flaid , no can stop um steamship .
#Text=Heap flaid too much talkee-talkee .
#Text=No stop ; go fish now ; go fish chop-chop .
#Text=Los ' heap time ; go fish .
#Text=I no savvy sail
#Text=um boat , China boy no savvy sail um boat .
#Text=I tink um you savvy ( and he pointed to Moran ) .
#Text=I tink um you savvy plenty heap much disa bay .
#Text=Boss number two , him no savvy sail um boat , but him savvy plenty many all same . '
#Text=“ And we 're to stop on board your dough-dish and navigate her for you ? ” shouted Moran , her face blazing .
#Text=Charlie nodded blandly :
#Text=“ I tink um yass . ”
#Text=“ And when we get back to port , ” exclaimed Wilbur , “ you think , perhaps I -- we wo n't make it interesting for you ? ”
#Text=Charlie smiled .
#Text=“ I tink um Six Company heap rich . ”
#Text=“ Well , get along , ” ordered Moran , as though the schooner was her property , “ and we 'll talk it over . ”
#Text=“ China boy like you heap pretty big , ” said Charlie to Moran , as he went out .
#Text=“ You savvy sail um boat all light ; wanta you fo ' captain .

#Text=But , ” he added , suddenly dropping his bland passivity as though he wore a mask , and for an instant allowing the wicked malevolent Cantonese to come to the surface , “ China boy no likee funnee business , savvy ? ”
#Text=Then with a smile of a Talleyrand he disappeared .
#Text=Moran and Wilbur were helpless for the present .
#Text=They were but two against seven Chinamen .
#Text=They must stay on board , if the coolies wished it ; and if they were to stay it was a matter of their own personal safety that the “ Bertha Millner ” should be properly navigated .
#Text=“ I 'll captain her , ” concluded Moran , sullenly , at the end of their talk .
#Text=“ You must act as mate , Mr. Wilbur .
#Text=And do n't get any mistaken idea into your head that , because I 'm a young girl and alone , you are going to run things your way .
#Text=I do n't like funny business any better than Charlie . ”
#Text=“ Look here , ” said Wilbur , complaining , “ do n't think I 'm altogether a villain .
#Text=I think you 're a ripping fine girl .
#Text=You 're different from any kind of girl I ever met , of course , but you , by jingo , you're -- you 're splendid .
#Text=There in the squall last evening , when you stood at the wheel , with your hair -- ”
